					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/lottery-of-babylon" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1367816); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1367816&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227439" alt="Lottery of Babylon" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1367816)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/lottery-of-babylon" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1367816); return false;" >Lottery of Babylon</a></span> <span class="odate time_1337887119 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">24 May 2012 19:18</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1458979">
									

<p>The Foundation being everywhere is a practical problem, but even if the Foundation were smaller, exposing them all to the same SCP is a really bad idea. What if it has unknown side-effects like <a href="/scp-884">SCP-884</a>? What if the first Foundation staff (other than the already-criminal D-class) it was used on turning out to be a Serpent's Hand conspirator wasn't just a coincidence, and this thing actually altered reality like <a href="/scp-1191">SCP-1191</a> to make that the case? The O5 personally avoid interaction with pretty much any SCP object for precisely that reason; none of them would ever even consider proposing something like this, even if we had a hundred copies of this briefcase and actually could expose every member of the Foundation to them.</p>

							</div>

								
